{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "A year after the fatal shooting of Michael Brown in Ferguson, Mo., interviews with residents, activists and academics suggest that forces perpetuating housing segregation remain present.", "abstract": "St Louis region, which has been absorbed in intense discussion of race and class since 2014 shooting of Michael Brown, continues to face pervasive housing segregation that prevents many black families from having same opportunities as whites; Ferguson Commission, convened by Missouri Gov Jay Nixon to address problem, has proposed measures to integrate communities, including stricter enforcement of fair housing laws and statewide ordinance prohibiting discrimination against renters with section 8 vouchers. ", "section_name": "U.S.", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "John", "role": "reported", "lastname": "ELIGON", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By JOHN ELIGON", "contributor": "Sarah Cohen contributed reporting from New York."}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/09/us/a-year-after-ferguson-housing-segregation-defies-tools-to-erase-it.html", "lead_paragraph": "A year after the fatal shooting of Michael Brown in Ferguson, Mo., interviews with residents, activists and academics suggest that forces perpetuating housing segregation remain present.", "headline": {"main": "A Year After Ferguson, Housing Segregation Defies Tools to Erase It", "print_headline": "An Indelible Black-and-White Line "}, "_id": "55c6395638f0d870ed943289", "word_count": "3183", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/08/09/us/09SEGREGATE-1/09SEGREGATE-1-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/08/09/us/09SEGREGATE-1/09SEGREGATE-1-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 399, "url": "images/2015/08/09/us/09SEGREGATE-1/09SEGREGATE-1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/08/09